  "success_stories": "On the first day of implementation, Flock Safety automated license plate reader (ALPR) cameras immediately demonstrated their value to the El Cajon Police Department with two successful apprehensions.\n\nOn July 28, 2023, a real-time alert notified officers that a vehicle stolen during a violent robbery and carjacking in Lemon Grove on July 22 had been detected by the ALPR system. Through rapid coordination between agencies, a San Diego County Sheriff\u0019s deputy located the vehicle within minutes and safely apprehended two suspects.\n\nLater that evening, another ALPR alert identified a vehicle that had been stolen during a commercial burglary in Winterhaven, California (Imperial County) on July 26. An El Cajon Police officer quickly located the occupied vehicle in a gas station parking lot and arrested the suspect without incident.\n\nThese two incidents on day one highlight how real-time ALPR technology can quickly connect crimes across jurisdictions and help officers safely and efficiently locate stolen vehicles and suspects.\n\nOn October 5, 2024, at approximately 9:15 PM, officers from the El Cajon Police Department responded to a reported stabbing in the 800 block of Benedict Avenue in El Cajon, California.Upon arrival, officers encountered a suspect armed with a knife. When officers attempted to detain him, the suspect fled on foot and attempted to carjack a passing motorist, who was able to escape. Officers continued searching the area and ultimately apprehended the suspect. He was taken into custody and booked into the San Diego County Sheriff's Office Central Jail.\n\nThe victim, a 71-year-old male, was found with a stab wound to his torso and transported to a nearby hospital. On October 12, the victim died from his injuries.\n\nDuring the investigation, detectives determined that the victim and suspect\u0014both homeless\u0014had recently met, and the victim had been giving the suspect a ride when their vehicle broke down. During the suspect\u0019s attempt to flee the scene, Flock Safety automated license plate reader cameras helped investigators identify the motorist the suspect attempted to carjack, providing critical witness information that supported the homicide investigation.\n\nOver the course of one month, a suspect committed at least eleven thefts at Food 4 Less, repeatedly entering the store, concealing groceries and health products, and leaving without paying. The total reported loss exceeded $4,000.\n\nA detective with the El Cajon Police Department developed a key lead when the suspect vehicle\u0019s license plate was identified and linked to surveillance footage from the store. The investigation led to the identification of a 39-year-old resident of unincorporated El Cajon who was also found to be selling the stolen merchandise. The vehicle\u0019s license plate was entered into the city\u0019s Flock Safety automated license plate reader system. On May 9, the system generated an alert when the vehicle was detected traveling southbound on North Mollison Avenue. A patrol officer quickly located and stopped the vehicle, confirmed the suspect as the driver, and took him into custody. He was later booked into the San Diego County Sheriff's Office Central Jail on charges including organized retail theft, grand theft, and conspiracy.\n\nOn February 29, 2024, at approximately 4:14 PM, the El Cajon Police Department responded to reports of gunfire at a dental office on North Magnolia Avenue in El Cajon, California. Officers arrived within minutes and located three victims suffering from gunshot wounds. Despite lifesaving efforts, one adult male died at the scene, while two additional victims were transported to the hospital in serious but stable condition.\n\nWitnesses reported that the suspect, a 29-year-old local resident and former patient of the dental office, fled in a white U-Haul pickup truck. Officers quickly utilized the city\u0019s Flock Safety automated license plate reader system, which captured an image of the vehicle and its license plate. Investigators rapidly identified the rental vehicle and confirmed it had been rented in San Diego.\n\nBecause this information was obtained so quickly, detectives were able to distribute the suspect vehicle\u0019s photo and license plate to the public through news media and department social media, which resulted in his arrest within hours after his murderous rampage.\n\nOn October 28, 2023, at approximately 11:57 PM, the El Cajon Police Department responded to multiple 9-1-1 calls reporting a large house party and gunshots in the 700 block of Mahogany Drive in El Cajon, California. Officers arrived to find numerous individuals fleeing the area and located two victims\u0014a 16-year-old male and an 18-year-old male\u0014suffering from critical gunshot wounds. Both victims later died after being transported to local trauma hospitals.\n\nHomicide detectives determined that at least two suspects fled the scene in a vehicle prior to police arrival. Investigators used the city\u0019s Flock Safety automated license plate reader cameras to identify the suspected getaway vehicle, which led to the identification of two suspects from San Diego.\n\nOne suspect was later taken into custody by the Chula Vista Police Department on November 18 during an unrelated firearm arrest. On November 20, officers and detectives from the El Cajon Police Department, with assistance from the United States Marshals Service Fugitive Task Force and the East County Regional Gang Task Force, located and arrested the second suspect in San Diego, bringing the homicide investigation closer to resolution.",
